menu "MicroLink V2 Configuration"

    config ML_ZERO_COPY_WG
        bool "Enable zero-copy WireGuard receive (high-throughput mode)"
        default n
        help
            Use raw lwIP UDP PCB instead of BSD sockets for WireGuard packet
            reception on the DISCO UDP socket. This eliminates memory copies
            and reduces latency by injecting WG packets directly into the
            WireGuard stack from the lwIP tcpip_thread.

            When enabled:
            - WireGuard packets: zero-copy direct injection (no malloc, no memcpy)
            - DISCO packets: lock-free SPSC ring buffer to wg_mgr task
            - STUN packets: still handled via BSD socket + queue

            Enable this for high-throughput applications like video streaming
            (30fps+). For typical IoT/sensor applications (heartbeats, commands),
            the default BSD socket mode is simpler and sufficient.

            Zero-copy mode contributed by dj-oyu (https://github.com/dj-oyu/microlink)

    config ML_MAX_PEERS
        int "Maximum simultaneous WireGuard peers"
        default 16
        range 1 64
        help
            Maximum number of peers with active WireGuard tunnels. Each peer
            uses approximately 200 bytes plus endpoint storage.

            Most deployments need 1-4 peers (only the peers you actively
            communicate with). For large tailnets, set this to the actual
            peer count needed, not the total tailnet size.

    config ML_PRIORITY_PEER_IP
        string "Priority peer VPN IP"
        default ""
        help
            Tailscale VPN IP of the priority peer (e.g., "100.81.222.123").
            This peer is guaranteed a WireGuard slot even when the peer table
            is full — the least-recently-used non-priority peer is evicted to
            make room.

            On large tailnets where the NVS cache fills the peer table at boot
            before the priority peer arrives from MapResponse, this ensures
            the peer you care about always gets a slot.

            Can also be set at runtime via the HTTP config server web UI.
            Leave empty to disable (all peers treated equally).

    config ML_NVS_MAX_PEERS
        int "Maximum cached peers in NVS"
        default 64
        range 16 1024
        help
            Maximum number of peers stored in the NVS flash cache. Peers are
            persisted across reboots so DISCO probing can start immediately
            before control plane registration completes.

            Storage is a single packed blob: each peer uses 92 bytes.
            When the cache is full, the least-recently-used peer is evicted.

            Examples:
            - 16:   ~1.5KB NVS blob (small IoT deployments)
            - 64:   ~5.9KB NVS blob (default, most tailnets)
            - 256:  ~23.6KB NVS blob (large tailnets)
            - 1024: ~94.2KB NVS blob (enterprise, requires large NVS partition)

            The blob is PSRAM-backed in memory. Ensure your NVS partition is
            large enough for the configured value.

    config ML_H2_BUFFER_SIZE_KB
        int "HTTP/2 receive buffer size (KB)"
        default 512
        range 64 2048
        help
            Size of the PSRAM-allocated buffer for receiving HTTP/2 frames
            from the Tailscale control plane (MapResponse).

            The initial MapResponse contains all peers in your tailnet.
            Each peer is roughly 1-2KB of JSON. After the initial response,
            delta updates (PeersChanged/PeersRemoved) are much smaller.

            - 64:   ~30 peers (small tailnets)
            - 512:  ~300 peers (default, most deployments)
            - 1024: ~600 peers (large enterprise tailnets)
            - 2048: ~1200 peers (very large tailnets, requires 8MB PSRAM)

    config ML_JSON_BUFFER_SIZE_KB
        int "JSON parse buffer size (KB)"
        default 512
        range 64 2048
        help
            Size of the PSRAM-allocated buffer for parsing JSON MapResponse
            data. cJSON builds an in-memory DOM tree that uses 2-3x the
            raw JSON size, so this should be at least as large as the
            HTTP/2 buffer.

            Match this to ML_H2_BUFFER_SIZE_KB unless you have a reason
            to set them differently.

    menu "Cellular Modem"

        config ML_ENABLE_CELLULAR
            bool "Enable cellular modem support"
            default n
            help
                Enable 4G cellular modem driver for MicroLink.
                Supports SIMCOM SIM7600 and SIM7670 series modems via UART
                AT socket bridge (AT+NETOPEN/CIPOPEN/CIPSEND).

                When enabled, MicroLink can operate over cellular data instead
                of (or in addition to) WiFi. All Tailscale protocol operations
                work unchanged — traffic is routed through DERP relay.

        choice ML_CELLULAR_BOARD
            prompt "Cellular board type"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_CELLULAR
            default ML_BOARD_WAVESHARE_SIM7600

            config ML_BOARD_WAVESHARE_SIM7600
                bool "Waveshare SIM7600X + XIAO ESP32S3"
                help
                    Waveshare SIM7600X 4G Module connected to Seeed XIAO ESP32S3.
                    Modem UART: TX=GPIO43, RX=GPIO44.
                    No power control pin needed (always on via USB-C).

            config ML_BOARD_LILYGO_T_SIM7670G
                bool "LILYGO T-SIM7670G-S3"
                help
                    LILYGO T-SIM7670G-S3 all-in-one board with integrated SIM7670G modem.
                    Modem UART: TX=GPIO11, RX=GPIO10.
                    Power control: PWRKEY=GPIO18, DTR=GPIO9, RESET=GPIO17.

            config ML_BOARD_CUSTOM
                bool "Custom pin configuration"
                help
                    Manually configure UART and power control GPIO pins.
        endchoice

        config ML_CELLULAR_TX_PIN
            int "Cellular UART TX GPIO pin"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_CELLULAR
            default 11 if ML_BOARD_LILYGO_T_SIM7670G
            default 43
            help
                GPIO pin for ESP32 TX -> modem RXD.
                Waveshare SIM7600X: GPIO43 (XIAO D6).
                LILYGO T-SIM7670G-S3: GPIO11.

        config ML_CELLULAR_RX_PIN
            int "Cellular UART RX GPIO pin"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_CELLULAR
            default 10 if ML_BOARD_LILYGO_T_SIM7670G
            default 44
            help
                GPIO pin for ESP32 RX <- modem TXD.
                Waveshare SIM7600X: GPIO44 (XIAO D7).
                LILYGO T-SIM7670G-S3: GPIO10.

        config ML_CELLULAR_PWRKEY_PIN
            int "Modem PWRKEY GPIO pin"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_CELLULAR
            default 18 if ML_BOARD_LILYGO_T_SIM7670G
            default -1
            help
                GPIO pin for modem power key control.
                Set to -1 if not connected (Waveshare: always-on via USB).
                LILYGO T-SIM7670G-S3: GPIO18.

        config ML_CELLULAR_DTR_PIN
            int "Modem DTR GPIO pin"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_CELLULAR
            default 9 if ML_BOARD_LILYGO_T_SIM7670G
            default -1
            help
                GPIO pin for modem Data Terminal Ready signal.
                Set to -1 if not connected.
                LILYGO T-SIM7670G-S3: GPIO9.

        config ML_CELLULAR_APN
            string "Cellular APN"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_CELLULAR
            default ""
            help
                Access Point Name for cellular data connection.
                Leave empty for auto-detection.

        config ML_CELLULAR_SIM_PIN
            string "SIM Card PIN"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_CELLULAR
            default ""
            help
                PIN code for the SIM card. Leave empty if no PIN required.

        config ML_CELLULAR_PPP_USER
            string "PPP CHAP username"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_CELLULAR
            default ""
            help
                Username for PPP CHAP authentication.
                Leave empty for SIMs that use IMSI-based auth (no credentials).
                Soracom SIMs use "sora".

        config ML_CELLULAR_PPP_PASS
            string "PPP CHAP password"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_CELLULAR
            default ""
            help
                Password for PPP CHAP authentication.
                Leave empty for SIMs that use IMSI-based auth (no credentials).
                Soracom SIMs use "sora".

    endmenu

    menu "Network Switching"

        config ML_ENABLE_NET_SWITCH
            bool "Enable WiFi/Cellular network switching"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_CELLULAR
            default n
            help
                Automatic WiFi-primary with cellular fallback.
                When WiFi connection fails or health check detects loss,
                switches to cellular. Periodically checks if WiFi has
                recovered and fails back.

        config ML_NET_SWITCH_WIFI_TIMEOUT_MS
            int "WiFi connect timeout (ms)"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_NET_SWITCH
            default 30000
            help
                How long to wait for WiFi connection before falling back
                to cellular.

        config ML_NET_SWITCH_HEALTH_INTERVAL_MS
            int "Health check interval (ms)"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_NET_SWITCH
            default 30000
            help
                Interval between health checks when connected.
                After 3 consecutive failures, triggers network switch.

        config ML_NET_SWITCH_FAILBACK_MS
            int "WiFi failback check interval (ms)"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_NET_SWITCH
            default 120000
            help
                When on cellular, how often to check if WiFi has recovered.
                Set to 0 to disable automatic failback.

    endmenu

    menu "Credentials"
        comment "Configure via: idf.py menuconfig → MicroLink V2 → Credentials"
        comment "These values are stored in sdkconfig (git-ignored)."

        config ML_WIFI_SSID
            string "WiFi SSID"
            default ""
            help
                SSID of the WiFi network to connect to.
                This is stored in sdkconfig which should be git-ignored.

        config ML_WIFI_PASSWORD
            string "WiFi Password"
            default ""
            help
                Password for the WiFi network.
                This is stored in sdkconfig which should be git-ignored.

        config ML_TAILSCALE_AUTH_KEY
            string "Tailscale Auth Key"
            default ""
            help
                Tailscale authentication key from https://login.tailscale.com/admin/settings/keys
                Generate a reusable + ephemeral key for development.
                This is stored in sdkconfig which should be git-ignored.

        config ML_DEVICE_NAME
            string "Device Name"
            default ""
            help
                Hostname for this device on the Tailscale network.
                Leave empty for auto-generated name (esp32-XXYYZZ from MAC,
                or prefix-IMEI from cellular modem).

    endmenu

    menu "HTTP Config Server"

        config ML_ENABLE_CONFIG_HTTPD
            bool "Enable HTTP configuration server"
            default n
            help
                Enable an HTTP server accessible via the Tailscale VPN IP
                (e.g., http://100.x.x.x/) for runtime configuration of
                WiFi credentials, Tailscale auth key, peer allowlist, etc.

                Settings persist in NVS across reboots. The peer allowlist
                controls which peers receive outbound DISCO probes — on large
                tailnets this prevents wg_mgr flooding and reduces latency.

        config ML_CONFIG_MAX_ALLOWED_PEERS
            int "Maximum peers in allowlist"
            depends on ML_ENABLE_CONFIG_HTTPD
            default 16
            range 1 1024
            help
                Maximum number of peers in the DISCO probe allowlist.
                Each entry uses 28 bytes in NVS (IP + 24-char label).
                ESP-IDF NVS supports multi-page blobs up to 508KB,
                so large allowlists are not a problem.

                - 16:    448 bytes (default, small deployments)
                - 128:   3.6KB
                - 300:   8.4KB (recommended for large fleets)
                - 1024:  28.7KB

                When the allowlist is empty, all peers are probed (backwards
                compatible). When populated, only listed peers receive
                outbound DISCO probes and WG peer table slots.

    endmenu

endmenu
